  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "l1-past-theory",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Regular and irregular past",
      "body": "# The past simple\n\nUse the **past simple** for finished actions: *Yesterday I worked.* (कल मैंने काम किया।)\n\n## Regular verbs: add -ed\n\n| Base | Past |\n|---|---|\n| play | **played** |\n| work | **worked** |\n| watch | **watched** |\n\n## Irregular verbs: a new form\n\nMany common verbs change completely — you must learn them:\n\n| Base | Past |\n|---|---|\n| go | **went** |\n| eat | **ate** |\n| buy | **bought** |\n| see | **saw** |\n\nUnlike Hindi, the English verb does **not** change for gender — *I went* / *she went* are the same."
    },
    {
      "id": "l1-questions-theory",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Questions and negatives with did",
      "body": "# Did for questions and negatives\n\nIn the past, questions and negatives use **did** — and the main verb goes back to its **base** form:\n\n- Statement: *I went.*\n- Question: **Did** you **go**? (not *Did you went?*)\n- Negative: *I **didn't go**.* (नहीं गया)\n\nSo only **did** carries the past; the main verb stays simple. This is different from Hindi, where the verb itself shows the tense."
    },
    {
      "id": "l1-ex-match-past",
      "type": "exercise",
      "theory_ref": "l1-past-theory",
      "title": "Match the past forms",
      "exercise": {
        "id": "l1-ex-match-past",
